            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Cody Sato\u2019s story is one of blended sensibilities, born from a practical Japanese-American father who ran an auto shop and a White American mother with an artist\u2019s heart, who filled their Petaluma home with thrift-store treasures. Growing up, Cody absorbed his father\u2019s pragmatism and his mother\u2019s eye for aesthetics, though he didn\u2019t know where this combination would lead. School was never his passion; he was more interested in working with his hands and observing how things fit together, whether it was an engine or a room\u2019s decor.\n\nForegoing a four-year university, he earned an Associate's in Business Administration from Santa Rosa Junior College, a no-nonsense degree he thought would guarantee a stable job. His first years in retail were uninspired stints at big-box stores, but a turning point came when he landed a stockroom job at a high-end menswear boutique in San Francisco. Here, his parents\u2019 worlds converged. He discovered a talent for visual merchandising and a genuine enjoyment in helping men find a personal style. Within a few years, his work ethic and natural eye for quality earned him the manager position.\n\nAt 25, Cody made the official move into the city, finding a rent-controlled one-bedroom in Hayes Valley, a neighborhood whose chic-but-grounded vibe instantly felt like home. His life now is a testament to intention. His 1.5-mile bicycle commute to the store is a cherished morning ritual, a breezy ride past Patricia\u2019s Green and the neighborhood\u2019s familiar faces. His days are spent managing staff, curating new inventory, and acting as a trusted stylist for his regulars. After work, he might meet his long-term partner, a graphic designer, for ramen or browse the local bookshop.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco is hyperlocal; he feels more a resident of Hayes Valley than of the city at large. At 31, Cody is content but not complacent. His quiet ambition, nurtured by years of hands-on experience, is to one day open his own shop\u2014a small, meticulously curated space for home goods and menswear. It\u2019s a daunting dream in an expensive city, but for Cody, it\u2019s the perfect synthesis of his heritage: a practical business built on a foundation of curated beauty."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 12, and his father handed him a heavy, grease-stained toolbox\u2014a rite of passage in the auto shop. But it was his mother who sat with him on their Petaluma porch, helping him painstakingly sand it down and paint it a deep, matte blue. Arranging his first set of wrenches inside, he felt a quiet click of understanding. It was the first time he realized that something purely practical could also be an object of personal beauty. That feeling of purpose and style intertwined never left him.\n\n***\n\n2.\nAt 23, hidden in the stockroom of the menswear boutique, he opened a shipment of Scottish cashmere. His past retail jobs had only involved plastic wrap and cardboard, but pulling a thick, charcoal-gray sweater from its tissue paper was a revelation. The softness, the weight, the perfect knit\u2014it felt like one of his mother\u2019s rare finds, but new. He wasn't just stocking a product; he was handling quality and intent. For the first time, a job felt like it truly fit him.\n\n***\n\n3.\nThe first morning in his Hayes Valley apartment at 25, the light slanted through the bay window in a way that felt entirely his own. The boxes were still stacked high, but he could hear the distant clatter of a cafe and the hum of the neighborhood waking up. He stood by the window next to his bicycle, a silent promise of the commute to come. It wasn't just a new apartment; it was the quiet, exhilarating feeling of having finally pulled into the right place.\n\n***\n\n4.\nTwo years ago, he was explaining his half-formed idea for a shop to his partner over ramen, describing the texture of Japanese ceramics next to rugged American-made jackets. His partner listened, then pulled out a napkin and sketched a simple logo combining a hanger and a teacup. Seeing his jumbled thoughts translated into a clear, beautiful design made his breath catch. His father\u2019s pragmatism and his mother\u2019s aesthetic, finally visualized. It wasn't just a dream anymore; it was a brand. It was possible.\n\n***\n\n5.\nSix months ago, bicycling home down a side street off Gough, he saw it: a small, empty storefront with a \"For Lease\" sign. The afternoon sun lit up the dust motes dancing inside. He stopped, one foot on the curb, and mentally placed everything\u2014a worn leather armchair here, shelves of selvedge denim there. A cold knot of fear formed in his stomach, but it was eclipsed by a fierce, practical desire. The ambition was no longer an abstract goal; it was a physical space waiting for him."
